  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Record of the Reconstruction of Baekryeonsa Temple on Mount Manduk
  author: Yun Hoe
  language: eng
  text: |-
    South of Kangchin County in Jeolla Province rises a mountain, bold and luminous, standing pristine and solemn until it meets the seashore—this is Mount Manduk. Upon its southern slope stands a temple, open and spacious, overlooking the boundless waters—this is Baekryeonsa.

    According to tradition, the temple was first established during the Silla era and restored by the esteemed Master Wonmyo of Goryeo. Through eleven generations it passed to the Venerable Master Muae, who maintained it as a Hall of the Lotus Scripture, earning it renown as a celebrated monastery of the Eastern realm. But when the Japanese pirates ravaged the land, all the territories near the sea were reduced to desolate wasteland, and the temple too declined with the fortunes of the age.

    Now in our Joseon, with sages succeeding one another, the mountains and seas rest in tranquility, and the dust of worldly turmoil no longer stirs. The Great Master Heo, Chief among Heaven-Terrace monks, came to visit Baekryeonsa and beheld its ruins. Leaning upon his staff, he sighed deeply, then resolved with fervent vow to restore what had fallen into decay—to revive its ancient glory and bring long life to the sovereign and fortune to the realm. He entrusted this mission to his disciple Sinseom and others, calling upon the faithful and generous to contribute their means. He dispatched Sinseom to present a memorial to Lord Hyolyeong, requesting him to become the principal patron. The lord graciously consented, and without hesitation gave forth both treasure and strength. People vied to follow, gathering from near and far. Jo Su, former official of Jangheung, and Kang Seup, headman of Kangchin, led the way.

    Work began in the autumn of Gyeongseul and was completed in the spring of Byeongsin. The Buddha Hall and monastic quarters were nearly restored to their former splendor, and the sacred ceremonies surpassed even the glory of old.

    The Master's family name is Choe, descended from the illustrious Minister of Culture. Though of noble lineage, he renounced the world in youth. His precepts were pristine, his understanding of the sublime dharma sudden and complete, earning reverence from all who wore the robe. When King Taejong commissioned the Gakrimsa Temple on Mount Chiok and held its dedication ceremony, he heard of the Master's renown and summoned him to preside. Later, when the king built the Great Compassion Hermitage by the tomb of Minister Byeon on Mount Jangnyeong, he appointed the Master as its abbot.

    When the present sovereign ascended the throne, he summoned the Master to oversee the Heaven-Terrace School. Yet the Master soon abandoned this position and withdrew to the mountains, such was his lofty spirit. His filial devotion was without equal—in caring for his mother in life and in arranging her burial with utmost reverence, he surpassed all other monks. The Golden Terrace and Anguk temples on Mount Duryu, the Sujeong temple on Mount Cheongwan—all were newly founded by him. And Baekryeonsa was his final achievement.

    Knowing of my friendship with the Master, Lord Hyolyeong entreated me to record this account. I could not refuse. May the merit of Lord Hyolyeong and Master Heo, joined with all the generous patrons who contributed, ripen in the boundless future, that they may together ascend to the Buddha realm and receive all its blessed rewards—and so it shall begin from this very moment.
  footnotes:
    - The Lotus Scripture (法華) refers to the Lotus Sutra, a central text in Mahayana Buddhism.
    - Master Wonmyo (圓妙) and Master Muae (無畏) were historically significant figures in Korean Buddhist history.
    - The Japanese pirates (倭敵) refer to the wokou raids that plagued Korean coasts during the Goryeo-Joseon transition.
    - Mount Chiok (雉岳山), also known as Jirisan, is one of Korea's most sacred mountains.
    - The Choe family of Saryang produced many prominent literati and officials, with Minister of Culture (文憲公) being an honorific title.
